1) How does HashMap work internally?

	HashMap in Java is implemented using an array of buckets.
	When we put a key-value pair, HashMap calls the hashCode() method of the key.
	The hash code is converted into an index using a hashing formula.
	The value is stored at that index (bucket).
	If multiple keys map to the same index (collision), they are stored using:
	Linked List (before Java 8)
	Balanced Tree (Red-Black Tree) 
	Average time complexity:
	get() → O(1)
	put() → O(1)
	
	2) What is load factor in HashMap?

	Load factor defines how full the HashMap can get before resizing.
	Default load factor = 0.75
	Formula:
	Capacity × Load Factor
	When the number of entries exceeds this value, the HashMap:
	Doubles its capacity
	Rehashes all entries
	Example:
	If capacity = 16
	Threshold = 16 × 0.75 = 12
	After 12 elements, resizing happens.
	Load factor balances:
	Memory usage
	Performance
	

3) What are Generics in Java?

	Generics in Java allow you to define classes, interfaces, and methods with a type parameter, so the type of data is specified at compile time.
	Generics in Java allow classes, interfaces, and methods to operate on different data types while providing compile-time type safety. 
	They eliminate type casting and improve code reusability.
	Generics is used for :
	To ensure compile-time type checking
	To avoid ClassCastException
	To remove unnecessary type casting
	To improve code reusability
	
	Example:
	ArrayList<String> list = new ArrayList<>();
	Here, only String objects are allowed.
	Generics were introduced in Java 5.
	They use angle brackets <T> to define type parameters.
	
4)Why are generics used?
Generics in Java are used to provide compile-time type safety and improve code reusability.
Before generics, collections stored data as Object, which required explicit type casting and could cause ClassCastException at runtime.
Generics help to:
Ensure type checking at compile time
Eliminate explicit type casting
Prevent runtime errors
Write reusable and flexible code
Example:
ArrayList<String> list = new ArrayList<>();


5)What is Type Safety? 
Type safety means ensuring that a variable, method, or collection can hold only a specific type of data, and any type mismatch is detected at compile time instead of runtime.
In Java, type safety is mainly achieved using generics.
Why is Type Safety Important?

Prevents ClassCastException
Detects errors during compilation
Makes code more reliable and secure
Reduces runtime failures
ArrayList list = new ArrayList();
list.add("Hello");
Integer num = (Integer) list.get(0); 